ce:section.ce:para:
FTIR analysis was utilized to investigate the surface chemical structure of S,NCQDs. In Fig. 2
                        , the peak at 3025 cm−1 corresponded to the vibration of CH on the aromatic ring of para-aminobenzoic acid [52]. The broad peak at 3674 cm−1 was ascribed to the stretching and vibration bands of OH [53,54]. The absorption peaks at 3118/1559, 1400 cm−1, and at 1624 cm−1, assigned to the stretching vibration bands of N-H, C-N, and C=N [55], respectively, provided evidence of successful further N-doping by ammonia sulfate on the surface of the CQDs. The occurrence of C=N as a result of the formation of pyridinic-N and pyrrolic-N due to the hydrothermal synthesis and doping process of N on the aromatic ring [38,45,56–58] was further explored by XPS analysis, which is discussed in a later section (Figure S2 and Fig. 3-4

                        ). For S doping, the stretching vibration bands of S=O and C-S at 1103 cm−1 and 615 cm−1, respectively, indicated the presence of sulfur-containing functional groups on the surface of the CQDs [38,59,60]. Collectively, the FTIR analysis demonstrated that S and N were introduced into the CQDs successfully, resulting in the formation of S- and N-containing functional groups through the interaction between para-aminobenzoic acid and ammonium sulfate.
